The file is the **GOLD SKILL** master specification for the `mini-theory-of-computation` project. Here's a summary of its contents:

## Core Philosophy
- **Dual Standard**: Every sub-module must have **≥3,000 lines** of real code (`include/` + `src/`) AND satisfy **nine-level knowledge coverage** (L1–L6 Complete, L7–L9 Partial+). Both are independently required.
- The project aims to implement the common core of theory-of-computation courses from: **MIT, Stanford, Berkeley, CMU, Princeton, Caltech, Cambridge, Oxford, ETH**.

## Nine Knowledge Levels (L1–L9)
| L1 | Definitions | P, NP, Turing machine, circuit family, reduction |
| L2 | Core Concepts | polynomial time, non-determinism, hierarchy, diagonalization |
| L3 | Math Structures | Boolean circuit DAG, DNF/CNF formulas |
| L4 | Fundamental Laws | Cook-Levin, Time Hierarchy, Savitch |
| L5 | Algorithms/Methods | DPLL SAT solving, switching lemma |
| L6 | Canonical Problems | SAT, 3SAT, CLIQUE, TQBF |
| L7 | Applications | cryptography, formal verification |
| L8 | Advanced Topics | PCP Theorem, circuit lower bounds |
| L9 | Research Frontiers | meta-complexity, GCT, quantum complexity |

## Anti-Filler Iron Law
Strictly prohibits: loop-generated stub functions (`_fn1.._fnN`), same-pattern functions repeated >3 times, Lean `by trivial` on non-trivial propositions, cross-file copy-paste, `sorry` in completed modules, and dead functions returning constants.

## Sub-module Structure
Each `mini-xxx/` must contain: `Makefile`, `README.md`, `include/` (≥4 headers), `src/` (≥4 C + ≥1 Lean), `tests/`, `examples/` (≥3), `demos/`, `benches/`, `docs/` (5 knowledge documents).

## Current Context
